This course explores the techniques that make a good magazine story, from the selection of topic, to the kind of reporting required, to the ways to recreate the vitality, importance and even humor of what readers see.&#8232;&#8232;
Students found this to be “one of the most interesting courses” taken at Penn, and the assigned readings “fantastic” and “funny,” despite the limitations in structure imposed by the writing seminar component. &#8232;&#8232;
Professor Rome is described as an “excellent professor” who was readily available outside of class to meet with students. Students felt she did a “great job” with the course, and explained the readings very well.&#8232;
&#8232;The assignments for this class were “unclear”, and the amount of work required was “a lot”. This course was recommended for majors, as well as non-majors.
